data.name: label2.Text
data.value: Vincent van Gogh (1853–1890) was a Dutch post-impressionist painter whose work, notable for its beauty, emotion, and color, highly influenced 20th-century art. He struggled with mental illness throughout his life and remained poor and virtually unknown, but his fame grew rapidly after his death. Today, van Gogh's paintings are some of the most expensive and popular artworks in the world.

data.name: label3.Text
data.value: Leonardo da Vinci was a Renaissance artist and inventor known for his iconic paintings such as the Mona Lisa and The Last Supper. He was also a scientist, mathematician, and writer, making significant contributions to anatomy, engineering, and various other disciplines. Da Vinci's work is celebrated for its technical mastery and profound artistic vision, making him one of the most influential figures in art history.

data.name: label4.Text
data.value: Pablo Picasso (1881–1973) was a Spanish painter, sculptor, printmaker, ceramicist, and stage designer who spent most of his adult life in France. He is known for co-founding the Cubist movement and for his innovative artistic endeavors across various styles and mediums. Picasso's work is characterized by a prolific output, unmatched in its diversity and depth, and his contributions to the development of modern art are unparalleled.
